{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496325"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.3,0.49,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97671"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"337"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5691"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5773"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9128"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department from a high level care home with two days of increasing abdominal pain. She has a medical history of a dense stroke six months ago which left her with aphasia and wheelchair dependence. She requires all her nutrition through a percutaneous gastrostomy tube. She has atrial fibrillation and takes warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and is unable to communicate. Her pulse rate is 96/min and irregularly irregular, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her abdomen demonstrates generalised guarding and rigidity consistent with peritonitis. A computed tomography scan shows extensive small bowel pneumatosis intestinalis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange transfer to the intensive care unit","Direct transfer to the operating room","Discuss palliative care with next of kin","Contact the general practitioner","Contact the nurse manager at the nursing home"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of mesenteric ischaemia and infarcted bowel, likely related to her atrial fibrillation. Given her severe pre-existing disability, poor functional status, and the extensive nature of the ischaemia, her chances of survival with surgical intervention would be extremely low. The focus should be on comfort care and dignified end-of-life management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussing palliative care with next of kin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. The medical team should take the lead in explaining the diagnosis, poor prognosis, and recommended palliative approach while ensuring the family understands and supports this decision. This allows for shared decision-making while maintaining medical leadership in determining appropriate care goals. The patient might have an Advanced Care Directive, which could make the decision-making easier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect transfer to the operating room\u003C/strong\u003E would subject the patient to futile surgery with extremely high mortality risk. Even if she survived the operation, her quality of life would likely be further diminished. Surgery in this setting could be considered an assault if not in the patient\u0027s best interests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging transfer to the intensive care unit\u003C/strong\u003E represents overly aggressive care that is unlikely to change the outcome. Intensive care admission would involve invasive monitoring, mechanical ventilation, and other interventions that would not alter the underlying pathology or improve her chances of meaningful recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContacting the general practitioner\u003C/strong\u003E may provide useful background information about the patient\u0027s wishes and previous discussions about end-of-life care. However, this should not delay immediate decision-making about appropriate care in this acute situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContacting the nurse manager\u003C/strong\u003E at the nursing home would similarly not assist with immediate clinical decision-making. While the nursing home staff may have valuable insights into the patient\u0027s recent function and quality of life, this information can be obtained after the immediate management plan is established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights several important principles in end-of-life care: the need to recognise futility, the importance of medical leadership in decision-making, and the balance between respecting patient autonomy and avoiding non-beneficial interventions. The finding of pneumatosis intestinalis (gas within the bowel wall) is a particularly poor prognostic sign in mesenteric ischaemia, associated with transmural bowel necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with severe comorbidities and poor functional status, palliative care may be more appropriate than aggressive intervention for acute surgical conditions","Medical teams should take the lead in end-of-life decision making rather than deferring difficult decisions to families","Clear communication with next of kin about prognosis and management plans is essential in end-of-life care","Pneumatosis intestinalis on CT indicates extensive bowel ischaemia and carries a very poor prognosis"],"references":["Karkkainen JM. Acute mesenteric ischemia: A challenge for the acute care surgeon. Scand J Surg 2021; 110:150\u201358","Lecroy K. The Lie of Primum non Nocere. Am Fam Physician. 2001; 64:1942"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97671"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18654"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18654"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de7df02f-20cb-4b60-b24d-d687a5d1cf6d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de7df02f-20cb-4b60-b24d-d687a5d1cf6d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":433}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97671"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T20:52:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T20:54:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"update